370
00:31:10,443 --> 00:31:18,185
[SPEAKER_01]: That results in an equity investment of roughly $62.7 million that they will be providing for this project.

371
00:31:20,016 --> 00:31:36,352
[SPEAKER_01]: The chart that we've included here essentially has some of the key terms of their investment that in reviewing the proposals MHA paid special attention to.

372
00:31:37,293 --> 00:31:38,694
[SPEAKER_01]: So the first question is

373
00:31:40,557 --> 00:31:43,418
[SPEAKER_01]: So enterprise acts as a syndicator.

374
00:31:43,438 --> 00:31:48,839
[SPEAKER_01]: That means that they are the middleman between you and the investor.

375
00:31:49,759 --> 00:31:54,060
[SPEAKER_01]: And so one key thing is always to ask, well, who is the investor?

376
00:31:55,020 --> 00:32:00,481
[SPEAKER_01]: Because you want an investor that you have a face and a name to.

377
00:32:00,601 --> 00:32:05,602
[SPEAKER_01]: And you want to make sure that there is a list in the industry of investors that

378
00:32:06,778 --> 00:32:10,159
[SPEAKER_01]: can be predatory and you want to avoid working with them.

379
00:32:10,439 --> 00:32:16,960
[SPEAKER_01]: So in this case, the investors are Citizens Bank, Cambridge Savings Bank, and First Republic Bank.

380
00:32:19,061 --> 00:32:34,044
[SPEAKER_01]: And as part of the investment, they will hold 99.99% of the MHA Saltonstall LC, which is essentially going to be holding the Saltonstall building.

381
00:32:36,122 --> 00:32:38,724
[SPEAKER_01]: MHA will be the managing member.

382
00:32:39,104 --> 00:32:51,132
[SPEAKER_01]: So there's a managing member that holds 0.01%, but essentially does all of the day-to-day work and makes the decisions for the project.

383
00:32:52,432 --> 00:32:57,235
[SPEAKER_01]: So that is the MHA SALT Install Manager, LLC.

384
00:33:00,497 --> 00:33:04,420
[SPEAKER_01]: So that's understanding the kind of overall structure of the investment.

385
00:33:05,617 --> 00:33:15,199
[SPEAKER_01]: A key question that came up in the selection of the equity investor was the question of who would service the guarantor.

386
00:33:15,799 --> 00:33:26,221
[SPEAKER_01]: And essentially what the investor looks is they want to make sure that the riskiest time for a development project is during construction.

387
00:33:26,861 --> 00:33:29,221
[SPEAKER_01]: What happens if construction prices go up?

388
00:33:29,381 --> 00:33:31,101
[SPEAKER_01]: What happens if there are change orders?

389
00:33:32,782 --> 00:33:34,282
[SPEAKER_01]: Who will cover that cost?

390
00:33:35,517 --> 00:33:46,167
[SPEAKER_01]: And then there are other guarantees related to making sure that the building operates at a break-even basis.

391
00:33:47,127 --> 00:33:56,996
[SPEAKER_01]: And so what they wanted was, in addition to having the Medford Housing Authority as a guarantor

392
00:33:57,767 --> 00:34:03,111
[SPEAKER_01]: to have the CHA join the FHA and act as joint guarantors.

393
00:34:03,771 --> 00:34:16,621
[SPEAKER_01]: And essentially, that's in part because the CHA is more experienced with light tech developments, and they also have a larger balance sheet.

394
00:34:17,541 --> 00:34:23,906
[SPEAKER_01]: And so the agreement that was negotiated with Enterprise was that

395
00:34:24,482 --> 00:34:34,230
[SPEAKER_01]: MHA and CHA would act as joint guarantors, but only until the last main guarantee expires.

396
00:34:34,871 --> 00:34:37,313
[SPEAKER_01]: And that's the operating deficit guarantee.

397
00:34:37,353 --> 00:34:41,757
[SPEAKER_01]: So making sure that the project reads even and that it can pay its debt service.

398
00:34:42,437 --> 00:34:50,504
[SPEAKER_01]: And that's expected to go away three years after the project completion of the permanent loan conversion.

399
00:34:53,039 --> 00:34:58,804
[SPEAKER_01]: So at that point, the expectation is that the CHA will step out of the guarantor structure.

400
00:35:00,025 --> 00:35:09,812
[SPEAKER_01]: But in terms of the managing member, that's going to be held, a majority of that will be held by the MHA, a smaller part by the CHA.

401
00:35:10,433 --> 00:35:16,257
[SPEAKER_01]: And this is a structure that's used in order to avoid related party issues.

402
00:35:16,538 --> 00:35:18,259
[SPEAKER_01]: And that has to do with

403
00:35:19,900 --> 00:35:30,183
[SPEAKER_01]: accounting and legal issues related to MHA providing a loan to the project and also being the original owner of the building.

404
00:35:30,343 --> 00:35:44,687
[SPEAKER_01]: And what it does is, it helps with MHA being able to have the investor exit the partnership in year 15, and I'll explain that more now.

405
00:35:46,048 --> 00:35:46,888
[SPEAKER_01]: So the way it works,

406
00:35:47,607 --> 00:35:58,729
[SPEAKER_01]: just generally with the tax credit program is that there's a 15-year compliance period for the low-income housing tax credits.

407
00:35:59,449 --> 00:36:12,272
[SPEAKER_01]: So that means that when I mentioned earlier that the investor will enter the MHA SALT Install LLC structure and hold 99.99%, they want to do that for 15 years because that's how long

408
00:36:17,646 --> 00:36:22,309
[SPEAKER_01]: the project needs to be in compliance with low-income housing tax credit rules.

409
00:36:23,370 --> 00:36:32,837
[SPEAKER_01]: However, after that 15 years, you, MHA, want the investor to exit, and you want to hold on to the building.

410
00:36:33,837 --> 00:36:44,385
[SPEAKER_01]: And so, essentially, what we negotiate with the equity investors is that there are multiple

411
00:36:46,828 --> 00:36:54,312
[SPEAKER_01]: multiple tools in your toolkit that you can use to have the investor exit and for you to have the building.

412
00:36:55,572 --> 00:37:15,702
[SPEAKER_01]: And I've listed some of these below, but essentially what the aim of these exit options is essentially for the Medford Housing Authority to be the sole owner of the LLC after 15 years at no cost or

413
00:37:16,352 --> 00:37:23,018
[SPEAKER_01]: a little cost, but the idea is to get you as many options so that you essentially have no cost.

414
00:37:23,838 --> 00:37:33,907
[SPEAKER_01]: And one of the best options is you have an option to purchase the building or purchase the interest by just assuming the loans.

415
00:37:34,487 --> 00:37:38,531
[SPEAKER_01]: So you're not paying anything for it, you're just taking on the loans that are remaining.

416
00:37:43,115 --> 00:37:44,336
[SPEAKER_01]: So I'm now at the,

417
00:37:45,208 --> 00:37:48,770
[SPEAKER_01]: bottom of that chart that says exit tax relief.

418
00:37:49,931 --> 00:37:53,752
[SPEAKER_01]: This year is related to when the investor exits at year 15.

419
00:37:55,974 --> 00:38:08,320
[SPEAKER_01]: There sometimes are situations where there's a tax that will be levied on some of the benefits that they've approved from the project in terms of depreciation.

420
00:38:09,321 --> 00:38:12,462
[SPEAKER_01]: And the negotiation here with

421
00:38:14,645 --> 00:38:22,929
[SPEAKER_01]: Enterprise is that if there is a need to exit tax relief, Enterprise will pay that and not the Medford Housing Authority.

422
00:38:25,310 --> 00:38:42,419
[SPEAKER_01]: And then the last, I think the last main thing to acknowledge is that the equity LOI has, it thinks that the Medford Housing Authority will continue to be the agency providing managers

423
00:38:42,689 --> 00:38:44,729
[SPEAKER_01]: and maintenance at Saltonstall.

424
00:38:47,270 --> 00:39:01,613
[SPEAKER_01]: And we're, you know, the Cambridge Housing Authority is available to provide some oversight and also mentoring to make sure that the Bedford Housing Authority is meeting the low-income housing tax credit rules.

425
00:39:06,394 --> 00:39:11,135
[SPEAKER_01]: So I think all in all captures

426
00:39:12,536 --> 00:39:15,779
[SPEAKER_01]: the memo that Jeff provided.

427
00:39:15,859 --> 00:39:23,845
[SPEAKER_01]: I'm happy to answer any questions or give more details about any particular item that's of interest.

428
00:39:29,429 --> 00:39:41,378
[SPEAKER_02]: Natalie, can you just address for the purposes of the board the aspect of the oversight that Cambridge would be providing in particular

429
00:39:42,580 --> 00:39:52,744
[SPEAKER_02]: as far as ensuring that the participants are certified and eligible for the low-income housing tax credit program.

430
00:39:53,584 --> 00:40:05,448
[SPEAKER_02]: And I'm basically looking to emphasize to the board that the difference today, as opposed to the way we qualify residents,

431
00:40:06,450 --> 00:40:29,778
[SPEAKER_02]: and what will transpire when one of those residents, for example, may not be eligible, and we may have to evict them, as opposed to someone who's not eligible for the low-income housing tax credit program, and so, therefore, we lose that credit, and I believe that is in the vicinity of, I want to guess and say $220,000.

432
00:40:29,818 --> 00:40:30,538
[SPEAKER_02]: Yeah, that's about right.

433
00:40:35,217 --> 00:40:38,438
[SPEAKER_01]: So that's a great question.

434
00:40:38,618 --> 00:40:53,240
[SPEAKER_01]: So essentially, it's true that the way that certifications are done under the low-income housing tax credit program is different from how it's done under public housing.

435
00:40:53,260 --> 00:41:03,142
[SPEAKER_01]: It's done at a very, there's specific forms that are required, and there's also different ways of calculating assets.

436
00:41:05,056 --> 00:41:09,258
[SPEAKER_01]: And this is something that all managers can learn.

437
00:41:10,218 --> 00:41:14,059
[SPEAKER_01]: But it takes some time to see how someone else is doing it.

438
00:41:14,099 --> 00:41:28,585
[SPEAKER_01]: So one thing that we've offered is that MHA staff can come over to some of our low-income housing tax credit developments and shadow the managers as they're completing.

439
00:41:29,587 --> 00:41:37,355
[SPEAKER_01]: these tax credit certifications in order to get a, you know, start to get a sense of how they're done.

440
00:41:37,475 --> 00:41:51,448
[SPEAKER_01]: It's really important to get these right because as Jeff just mentioned, these certifications go to the state and essentially the way that the tax credit program works,

441
00:41:51,988 --> 00:42:02,692
[SPEAKER_01]: is that it's based on the number of units in your building that have households that qualify for the low-income housing tax credit program.

442
00:42:03,392 --> 00:42:14,716
[SPEAKER_01]: And that is, that $62 million that I mentioned earlier, is funding that Enterprise will be providing the MHA during construction.

443
00:42:15,976 --> 00:42:21,298
[SPEAKER_01]: And it's based on what they think the credits will be over 10 years.

444
00:42:22,235 --> 00:42:49,690
[SPEAKER_01]: So what happens is if you make a mistake in the tax credit certification and that unit is no longer eligible, then that tax credit unit, that unit will no longer be part of the project and essentially your amount of credits will be deducted and that is a big loss to Enterprise and ultimately it gets pushed down onto

445
00:42:51,453 --> 00:43:00,339
[SPEAKER_01]: the managing member, because it's the managing member's responsibility to make sure that the tax credit certifications are done correctly.

446
00:43:02,040 --> 00:43:17,731
[SPEAKER_01]: So the idea is, moving forward, that the CHA will work with the MHA to figure out a way that a CHA can provide some oversight of looking through the tax credit certification, providing some

447
00:43:18,378 --> 00:43:21,239
[SPEAKER_01]: mentoring and training as is necessary.

448
00:43:21,859 --> 00:43:33,622
[SPEAKER_01]: But the idea, too, would be to have a third party who's an expert on tax credit certifications review those forms before they're sent out to the state.

449
00:43:33,662 --> 00:43:39,083
[SPEAKER_01]: So you have two levels of, you know, double checking.

450
00:43:39,203 --> 00:43:47,965
[SPEAKER_01]: So the CHA will double check them and then the third party and then it gets sent on to the state.

451
00:43:50,732 --> 00:44:00,156
[SPEAKER_02]: Whereas today, if we find, as I said, we find someone who is not eligible, we can go forward and evict them.

452
00:44:01,077 --> 00:44:04,278
[SPEAKER_02]: And we still get a subsidy from the federal government.

453
00:44:04,898 --> 00:44:19,045
[SPEAKER_02]: What Natalie is saying right now is that if we do something incorrectly and it ends up voiding part of that credit, we actually will be

454
00:44:19,942 --> 00:44:21,743
[SPEAKER_02]: there's a fine with that, correct?

455
00:44:21,823 --> 00:44:25,386
[SPEAKER_02]: Or there's a loss of income going forward during that 10-year period.

456
00:44:25,426 --> 00:44:26,246
[SPEAKER_02]: Am I correct on that?

457
00:44:27,707 --> 00:44:38,835
[SPEAKER_01]: So we essentially have to pay back the investor for the credits that they thought that they were going to get, but the project could not deliver.

458
00:44:40,616 --> 00:44:42,017
[SPEAKER_01]: And that is essentially

459
00:44:42,572 --> 00:44:48,696
[SPEAKER_01]: you know, that is finding money within a budget or the MHA's budget to pay that back.

460
00:44:49,476 --> 00:44:56,881
[SPEAKER_01]: It's a scenario that can easily be avoided by having these double and triple checks.

461
00:45:03,205 --> 00:45:04,245
[SPEAKER_02]: But it's significant.

462
00:45:04,345 --> 00:45:06,847
[SPEAKER_02]: It's the significance of that management approach.

463
00:45:07,580 --> 00:45:09,081
[SPEAKER_02]: which will ensure that it will not.

464
00:45:09,381 --> 00:45:23,831
[SPEAKER_02]: And having the CHA as an advisor, and just for the board's information, I know Natalie's aware of this, I met with the executive director of Cambridge, and Margaret Moran, who is the assistant executive director in charge of planning and development, correct?

465
00:45:23,851 --> 00:45:24,872
[SPEAKER_02]: Am I right on that, Natalie?

466
00:45:24,892 --> 00:45:25,893
[SPEAKER_02]: Am I close enough on that?

467
00:45:27,843 --> 00:45:51,080
[SPEAKER_02]: Okay, I met with them today to go over this and to discuss what the ramifications of this are and we have agreed for counsel that we've been using on this project to present to us and to move forward with a contract that I will present to the board that will illustrate what the relationship would be.

468
00:45:52,161 --> 00:45:56,103
[SPEAKER_02]: I'm very comfortable with the fact, Natalie, and I mentioned this today to Michael and

469
00:45:57,570 --> 00:46:17,357
[SPEAKER_02]: Margaret that the relationship that we have with Cambridge will continue because I would have wanted, even if it weren't required by Enterprise, I would have wanted Cambridge to continue with some sort of an oversight function and in some capacity because of your expertise and our lack of that expertise.

470
00:46:17,797 --> 00:46:19,118
[SPEAKER_02]: When this program first started,

471
00:46:20,398 --> 00:46:31,323
[SPEAKER_02]: the low-income housing tax credits were readily being provided to entities, and I use that word purposely, entities that didn't have the experience because there wasn't that experience out there.

472
00:46:32,024 --> 00:46:41,148
[SPEAKER_02]: What it's evolved to though at this point is there aren't a lot of housing authorities out there that are doing what we're doing and with the assistance of Cambridge we're able to do that.

473
00:46:41,548 --> 00:46:45,350
[SPEAKER_02]: We do see though the private companies out there

474
00:46:45,810 --> 00:46:51,612
[SPEAKER_02]: who are participating in this and who are getting the tax credits because they have that experience.

475
00:46:53,812 --> 00:46:56,953
[SPEAKER_02]: Are we overlooked because we're a public housing authority?

476
00:46:56,993 --> 00:46:57,253
[SPEAKER_02]: Yes.

477
00:46:57,674 --> 00:47:03,595
[SPEAKER_02]: But what Cambridge is doing, not only with us but with others, is putting us in a position to be able to do this going forward.

478
00:47:04,015 --> 00:47:09,157
[SPEAKER_02]: And when Walkley comes along, we may have enough of a track record at that point in time to do this.

479
00:47:09,623 --> 00:47:12,785
[SPEAKER_02]: without having that guarantee from Cambridge.

480
00:47:12,825 --> 00:47:28,236
[SPEAKER_02]: And let me just tell you, that guarantee is probably going to be in the vicinity, it's 10%, as I understand it, Natalie, and correct me if I'm wrong, but it's approximately 10% of the total award of the low-income housing tax credit.

481
00:47:28,816 --> 00:47:31,718
[SPEAKER_02]: And there would have to be funds set aside for that.

482
00:47:32,579 --> 00:47:33,459
[SPEAKER_02]: And that may be at a 50-50.

483
00:47:35,277 --> 00:47:46,341
[SPEAKER_02]: Breakdown, it may be a little bit more, a little bit less on one side of the ledger or the other, but Cambridge is going to put up collateral for that, just like we're going to through what will be our development fee that we will get.

484
00:47:46,641 --> 00:47:50,343
[SPEAKER_02]: Natalie, if I misspeak, please let me, you know, please don't hesitate to break in.

485
00:47:50,923 --> 00:48:02,207
[SPEAKER_02]: But Cambridge is willing to actually put that money up and have that money available in case one of the aspects of the guarantee do not come forward.

486
00:48:03,163 --> 00:48:06,325
[SPEAKER_02]: Am I close to being right on that, Natalie?

487
00:48:06,625 --> 00:48:07,906
[SPEAKER_02]: Did I interpret that correctly?

488
00:48:07,926 --> 00:48:13,330
[SPEAKER_01]: I think you have more up-to-date information, but that sounds correct.

489
00:48:13,470 --> 00:48:14,791
[SPEAKER_01]: Okay.

490
00:48:14,831 --> 00:48:18,053
[SPEAKER_02]: Theoretically, from a theoretical point, was I correct there?

491
00:48:18,693 --> 00:48:19,894
[SPEAKER_01]: No, you were correct.

492
00:48:19,974 --> 00:48:20,315
[SPEAKER_02]: Okay.

493
00:48:20,935 --> 00:48:21,715
[SPEAKER_01]: I have a question.

494
00:48:21,736 --> 00:48:32,763
[SPEAKER_01]: The idea really here is, it is, as Jeff mentioned, it is challenging to enter the space without having done

495
00:48:33,310 --> 00:48:35,652
[SPEAKER_01]: a low-income housing tax credit before.

496
00:48:36,492 --> 00:48:43,797
[SPEAKER_01]: And public housing authorities, you know, I think that have an unfair reputation.

497
00:48:44,538 --> 00:48:59,028
[SPEAKER_01]: And so, ultimately, and also the challenge of having, as a public housing authority, you have a balance sheet, but you have a lot of funding that's there that before you became

498
00:48:59,975 --> 00:49:02,776
[SPEAKER_01]: moving to work agency was restricted funding.

499
00:49:03,516 --> 00:49:12,637
[SPEAKER_01]: So there wasn't a lot of unrestricted cash that could be available to provide these guarantees that we briefly discussed earlier.

500
00:49:13,537 --> 00:49:27,280
[SPEAKER_01]: And so the idea really is to have the CHA be able to come in and help as much as is possible to get the project over the finish line and complete, but essentially step out

501
00:49:27,957 --> 00:49:49,431
[SPEAKER_01]: in order so that the MHA, the next time there's a project that requires a low-income housing tax credit investor, you now have the experience of showing that you've done this, that you know how to do the tax credit certifications, that you know how to manage a construction project of this scale.

502
00:49:50,031 --> 00:49:56,355
[SPEAKER_01]: And it starts to open up the doors for the MHA to do more of these projects on its own.

503
00:49:58,657 --> 00:50:23,899
[SPEAKER_02]: And if I can just add to that, the housing authorities that are getting involved in low-income housing tax credits that are not going the same route that we are going, end up foregoing the ownership of the units to a private entity who comes in, has that LIHTC experience, and who works with them to redevelop the properties, but then they take the units.

504
00:50:24,932 --> 00:50:25,833
[SPEAKER_02]: Then they take the units.

505
00:50:25,994 --> 00:50:31,802
[SPEAKER_02]: In our case, we'll have a ground lease with the LLC.

506
00:50:32,604 --> 00:50:35,248
[SPEAKER_02]: And the housing authority will continue to manage the property.

507
00:50:35,288 --> 00:50:37,271
[SPEAKER_02]: There'll be no private developer who will come in.

508
00:50:41,058 --> 00:50:42,559
[SPEAKER_05]: Hi Natalie, I have a question.

509
00:50:43,700 --> 00:50:55,048
[SPEAKER_05]: Are you aware or can you give us some information what will make a tenant not qualify for the tax credit or no longer qualify for the tax credit if they were already a tenant?

510
00:50:56,549 --> 00:50:57,810
[SPEAKER_05]: Do you have any information on that?

511
00:50:59,323 --> 00:51:08,247
[SPEAKER_01]: Yeah, so, well, first of all, I just want to start off by saying that all current residents of Salton Staub will have the right to return.

512
00:51:08,928 --> 00:51:27,057
[SPEAKER_01]: And so, Jen McNabb has been looking at all of the residents and their incomes and assets to see where they fall in the category, because for the low-income housing tax credit program, technically, you have to be earning 60% of the area median income or below.

513
00:51:28,837 --> 00:51:37,079
[SPEAKER_01]: There are some residents at Saltonstall who earn above that, but below 80% of area median income.

514
00:51:37,619 --> 00:51:46,400
[SPEAKER_01]: And what we built into, and there's a separate rule within the low-income housing tax credit program that can allow those residents.

515
00:51:47,221 --> 00:51:54,522
[SPEAKER_01]: So we built that into the agreement with Enterprise that there will be units that are available for

516
00:51:55,267 --> 00:52:04,775
[SPEAKER_01]: those salt and stone households who are between 60 and 80% of AMI so that they can return.

517
00:52:05,635 --> 00:52:17,085
[SPEAKER_01]: The major difference, as I understand it, between the tax credit or the certifications on the public housing side and the low-income housing side is just how assets are calculated.

518
00:52:17,105 --> 00:52:21,829
[SPEAKER_01]: And what you're typically looking is the ones where

519
00:52:22,940 --> 00:52:32,304
[SPEAKER_01]: You know, it may be, you know, that require more focus are the households that are just below 60% of AMI.

520
00:52:32,604 --> 00:52:39,727
[SPEAKER_01]: Because then you want to get a real good, you want to essentially go through the tax credit certification process to make sure that they're below that.

521
00:52:40,407 --> 00:52:43,748
[SPEAKER_01]: But a lot of your households are below 60% of AMI.

522
00:52:46,875 --> 00:52:48,116
[SPEAKER_01]: with some buffer there.

523
00:52:48,636 --> 00:52:58,661
[SPEAKER_01]: And then for the other households that are above there, below 80%, we built in the flexibility needed to let everyone have a right to come back.

524
00:52:59,322 --> 00:52:59,742
[SPEAKER_05]: Thank you.

525
00:53:01,203 --> 00:53:04,404
[SPEAKER_02]: Good question, Melissa.

526
00:53:04,464 --> 00:53:07,326
[SPEAKER_06]: Has the CHA been a guarantor in a project similar to this before?

527
00:53:10,161 --> 00:53:12,723
[SPEAKER_01]: If the CHA has been a guarantor of similar projects?

528
00:53:12,783 --> 00:53:13,984
[SPEAKER_06]: Yeah, something similar.

529
00:53:14,564 --> 00:53:14,764
[SPEAKER_06]: Yes.

530
00:53:15,025 --> 00:53:16,586
[SPEAKER_02]: Outside of Cambridge, correct?

531
00:53:17,406 --> 00:53:17,506
[SPEAKER_06]: Yeah.

532
00:53:17,546 --> 00:53:20,469
[SPEAKER_06]: Have you done this with other housing authorities or other agencies?

533
00:53:22,190 --> 00:53:28,735
[SPEAKER_01]: No, so this is our first time acting as a guarantor for non-CHA projects.

534
00:53:30,233 --> 00:53:35,634
[SPEAKER_01]: So we ourselves have done roughly $350 million in line type developments.

535
00:53:36,434 --> 00:53:47,736
[SPEAKER_01]: Most of our portfolio at this point has been comprehensively renovated using low-income housing tax credits, and we provided guarantees on those projects.

536
00:53:47,836 --> 00:53:56,398
[SPEAKER_01]: But it is the first new step for us to work with another housing authority to support them in providing guarantees.

537
00:53:57,378 --> 00:53:57,838
[SPEAKER_06]: That's great.

538
00:54:02,220 --> 00:54:24,464
[SPEAKER_02]: And your executive director, I think I mentioned this to the board, but the executive director, Michael, had indicated today that your board had unanimously endorsed doing this with Medford and putting the Cambridge financial ledger sheet up as a guarantor in this instance.

539
00:54:27,305 --> 00:54:28,485
[SPEAKER_02]: Is there a cost for this?

540
00:54:29,718 --> 00:54:32,239
[SPEAKER_02]: There will be a cost, we're still negotiating that.

541
00:54:32,279 --> 00:54:32,679
[SPEAKER_02]: With Cambridge.

542
00:54:32,859 --> 00:54:34,080
[SPEAKER_02]: Yes, yeah, with Cambridge.

543
00:54:34,740 --> 00:54:48,165
[SPEAKER_02]: But that cost will include not only the guarantee that they're going to provide, but also the staff assistance in oversight, relocation, things such as that.

544
00:54:48,965 --> 00:54:49,906
[SPEAKER_06]: Is that the contract you?

545
00:54:50,726 --> 00:54:52,547
[SPEAKER_02]: That I referenced, yeah.

546
00:54:52,587 --> 00:54:53,767
